(1) Ilya Sutskever Has a New Plan for Safe Superintelligence [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/33b27a04-b9b2-444b-a8c6-e85cbd6037c7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Ashlee Vance for Bloomberg Businessweek
Now Sutskever is introducing that project, a venture called Safe Superintel=
ligence Inc. [ https://substack.com/redirect/caeecb02-ebb9-416e-9140-cb0f0b=
31a436?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 aiming to create a safe, powerful artificial intelligence system within a =
pure research organization that has no near-term intention of selling AI pr=
oducts or services. In other words, he=E2=80=99s attempting to continue his=
 work without many of the distractions that rivals such as OpenAI, Google a=
nd Anthropic face.
Here=E2=80=99s Ilya!
On Wednesday, Ashlee Vance of Bloomberg profiled the former OpenAI cofounde=
r=E2=80=99s next project, Safe Superintelligence (SSI). SSI is a research-f=
ocused lab with the objective of introducing =E2=80=9Csafe superintelligenc=
e=E2=80=9D to the world. Notably, the company plans to not release any near=
-term, potentially profitable products on the road to safe superintelligenc=
e. It=E2=80=99s SSI or bust!
The SSI team is predictably stacked, with Sutskever leading the charge, joi=
ned by AI entrepreneur-turned-investor Daniel Gross and former OpenAI young=
 gun Member of the Technical Staff Daniel Levy. With this bench and mission=
, the company won=E2=80=99t have any trouble attracting talent or capital.
We=E2=80=99re all for it. The more supergeniuses we have competing to deliv=
er humans more and more capable assistants, the better, as Packy wrote on T=
uesday [ https://substack.com/redirect/05a8f459-37e8-48f2-920a-d9002e928fdd=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Whether or not this approach towards developing safe superintelligence will=
 work is still very much TBD. It seems to me that much of the momentum arou=
nd AI over the last couple of years is due to the fact that products are be=
ing launched quickly, customers are giving feedback, there=E2=80=99s compet=
itive pressure to up product quality, and, of course, there is real revenue=
 involved. SSI is fully checking out of that rat race.=20
I guess we=E2=80=99ll see them on the other side.=20
Packy Note: Not to be outdone, Anthropic, which is trying to make some mone=
y before achieving Superintelligence, released its newest model, Claude 3.5=
 Sonnet [ https://substack.com/redirect/9b5f7309-98ee-4124-9217-af04ca43dc9=
2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], yes=
terday. Claude 3 Opus has been my favorite writing assistant, it=E2=80=99s =
much nicer to talk to than ChatGPT and gives better feedback on essays. Aft=
er playing around with 3.5 Sonnet for a bit, it=E2=80=99s even better and f=
aster. If you=E2=80=99ve only played with ChatGPT, I highly recommend tryin=
g out Claude [ https://substack.com/redirect/a972ce23-0d0a-4c79-b635-541beb=
78e1fd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
=2E=20
(2) Congress votes to advance nuclear=C2=A0energy=C2=A0development in the U=
S [ https://substack.com/redirect/383bbe3c-22f8-4c8b-b911-f10fb549b109?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Justine Calma for The Verge
The ADVANCE Act directs the Department of Energy (DOE) to streamline its pr=
ocess for approving the international export of American nuclear energy tec=
hnology and cut down regulatory costs for companies trying to license advan=
ced nuclear reactors. It creates incentives for successfully deploying thos=
e technologies, and tasks the Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) with crea=
ting a =E2=80=9Ctimely=E2=80=9D pathway for licensing small reactors at bro=
wnfields and former fossil fuel generator sites. It also seeks to accelerat=
e licensing review for new reactors at existing nuclear sites and streamlin=
e the environmental review process.
Congress just passed the ADVANCE Act, which aims to supercharge nuclear ene=
rgy development in the US. Fewer restrictions, less delays, more building. =
The bill, now awaiting Biden's signature, is designed to speed up the appro=
val of next-gen reactors and keep old ones running, like Diablo Canyon pict=
ured above. The bill also makes it easier and cheaper for companies to get =
licenses for advanced nuclear reactors and export American nuclear tech.=20
As the world (hopefully) continues its march towards a nuclear future, the =
bill is designed to ensure that the U.S. is the leader in nuclear. At home,=
 we need to actually start building nuclear plants and encouraging (or at l=
east not killing on arrival) innovative approaches to nuclear. And abroad, =
the U.S. should be the leading exporter of nuclear energy and technologies.
Importantly, the Act contains language that changes the NRC=E2=80=99s missi=
on from essentially avoiding risks at all costs to making nuclear as safe a=
s possible while considering the risk of not deploying nuclear. Thousands o=
f people die every year from fossil fuels; nuclear saves lives.=20
(2a) DOE doles out $900 million for next-gen small modular reactor deployme=
nt [ https://substack.com/redirect/ee02b016-6e62-4d12-90d3-ef1181414bdf?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Sean Wolfe for Power Engineering
The U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) issued a=C2=A0Notice of Intent (NOI) [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/e5897803-8704-448c-b9e5-2d9c34755286?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=C2=A0to fund u=
p to $900 million to support the initial U.S. deployments of Generation III=
+ small modular reactor (SMR) technologies.
Speaking of American nuclear leadership, the Department of Energy just anno=
unced $900 million in funding to support to development and deployment of s=
mall modular reactors (SMRs). As a reminder, a SMR is a compact, often a li=
ttle more factory-built nuclear power plant designed for smaller-scale elec=
tricity generation. Unlike traditional large reactors, SMRs can offer great=
er flexibility, lower upfront costs, and enhanced safety features, making t=
hem suitable for remote locations and scalable power needs.
The funding is being doled out across two stages:
An initial $800M will be awarded to two first-mover teams that are committe=
d to deploying a first plant.
An additional $100M will be awarded to fast-follower teams to spur addition=
al SMR deployments.
The DoE has been leading the charge on promoting nuclear since before the r=
est of the US Government realized it was cool. Someone give Jigar what he w=
ants [ https://substack.com/redirect/56a07c48-fbd4-4131-b8be-3bf6402d0baa?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]!=20
(3) The Dawn of the Solar Age [ https://substack.com/redirect/5a36e91a-596e=
-4a69-a251-25d8aeab46de?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From The Economist
Solar cells will in all likelihood be the single biggest source of electric=
al power on the planet by the mid 2030s. By the 2040s they may be the large=
st source not just of electricity but of all energy. On current trends, the=
 all-in cost of the electricity they produce promises to be less than half =
as expensive as the cheapest available today.
Here comes the sun=E2=80=A6 Lest you=E2=80=99re tempted to accuse us of bei=
ng nuclear maxis, we love catching energy by catching rays, too. So too, no=
w, does The Economist, which put out a special issue yesterday titled, The =
Dawn of the Solar Age.=20
If you=E2=80=99ve been reading the Weekly Dose, you=E2=80=99ve known all ab=
out solar=E2=80=99s stellar ascent, thanks to pieces from Not Boring=E2=80=
=99s favorite sun-worshippers, Casey Handmer and Noah Smith. But it=E2=80=
=99s cool to see it in one place.=20
And it=E2=80=99s particularly cool to see a chart like this one:=20
Experts just keep underestimating=E2=80=99s solar=E2=80=99s potential, on a=
verage by three times, even in the very near future.=20
Exponentials are hard to grok, but sometimes, you just gotta trust the curv=
e.=20
(4) Boom Supersonic Completes Construction of the Overture Superfactory [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/86a1c407-4e70-48e4-a477-89c3cd81876e?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Boom
Boom Supersonic marked the completion of construction on its Overture Super=
factory with a ribbon-cutting ceremony on June 17, 2024. Located at the Pie=
dmont Triad International Airport [ https://substack.com/redirect/0d7a5738-=
4e7a-4768-81b4-fa8ce19d581e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in Greensboro, North Carolina, the Overture Superfact=
ory is the first supersonic airliner factory in the United States. The stat=
e-of-the-art assembly line is where Boom will build its supersonic airliner=
, Overture.
Elon often reminds us: manufacturing is actually the hard thing.
Boom, the supersonic airline, is doing hard things.
The company completed the construction of its new Overture Superfactory, wh=
ere it will build its supersonic airliner. Overture should be capable of tr=
aveling at Mach 1.7 (1,122 mph) and carrying 64-80 passengers over a range =
of 4,250 nautical miles. It=E2=80=99s the new age Concorde. New York to Lon=
don is 3.5 hours. Totally changes the game for transatlantic flight.
The new superfactory, located at Piedmont Triad International Airport in Gr=
eensboro, North Carolina, is the first supersonic airliner factory in the U=
=2ES. With a production capacity of 33=20=
aircraft annually and plans to double,=
 it is expected to contribute over $32 billion to the local economy and cre=
ate 2,400 jobs over the next 20 years.
Cannot wait to go Booming across the world.
(5) JC Btaiche: CEO and Founder of Fuse [ https://substack.com/redirect/dc6=
3f387-ee11-4a8c-844d-88bc8d6ea152?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Plymouth
While working in the aforementioned physics lab JC couldn=E2=80=99t help bu=
t to dream bigger. He wanted to explore the universe, so he asked his profe=
ssor =E2=80=9CI want to build fusion powered rockets, how do I start?". The=
 professor put it bluntly "you need to immigrate". It was in this short exc=
hange that JC=C2=A0learned in order to build something big it was going to =
require a move out west.
Packy here. Earlier this week, I got to meet Lisa Wehden [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/94f9946b-5d9b-447c-a61=
1-527c01483cf3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the founder of Plymouth [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/79d948ae-00a5-471e-ac11-bada2b44444d?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. I=E2=80=99d seen=
 Lisa all over Twitter =E2=80=94 it seems like any time a talented immigran=
t announces that they got their visa, they=E2=80=99re thanking her for maki=
ng it happen.=20
I love America and I love technology. I want to see America recruit the wor=
ld=E2=80=99s most talented technologists as hard as an SEC booster recruits=
 a 6=E2=80=992=E2=80=9D Texan high schooler with a cannon for a right arm. =
Instead, we make the process of high-skilled immigration as hard and painfu=
l as possible.=20
Plymouth is making it easier with the Plymouth O-1A Accelerated Pathway. Th=
ey help the world=E2=80=99s best prepare, finalize, and submit their applic=
ation in just four weeks. So far, they=E2=80=99ve received 115 approvals, w=
ith a 99% approval rate.=20
This isn=E2=80=99t an ad for Plymouth, I just want every talented internati=
onal engineer or potential founder reading this to know that Plymouth exist=
s, so that you can get over here and help build the future.=20
One of the people Plymouth helped bring to America is Not Boring favorite, =
recent Deep Dive [ https://substack.com/redirect/5543b503-a99a-4388-b36b-25=
7b6bf4d250?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] and Weekly Dose [ https://substack.com/redirect/8dcf6007-798c-4101-9e5=
6-fdf5729b32a5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ] star, JC Btaiche, the founder of Fuse Energy. This week, Plymouth =
dropped a profile on JC=E2=80=99s journey.=20
America is obviously better off for having people like JC working here. Her=
e=E2=80=99s to Plymouth 100x=E2=80=99ing the number of JC=E2=80=99s in Amer=
ica in the coming years.=20
Have a great weekend y=E2=80=99all.
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday.
Thanks for reading,
Packy + Dan

